She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Do you keep re-reading memories?", Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's almost in just a few days."
Kari hit the lantern twice. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out, as he considered her "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only daughter of the family, otherwise composed only of boys.
Ivory was like that too, in her own way. When she had spoken of her non-binary status, it was as if the world had changed too. They had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude as a punishment for her difference.
She was also required to stay in service with the princess, but that wasn't very serious, as it made her a friend.
"It's almost your birthday, isn't it?", Ivory asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was just a few days away. Kari nodded her head, a sorrowful glint in her pale blue eyes.
"Are you going to celebrate it?" As she asked the question, she remembered what she had replied to him the last time.
No, Kari struck Ivory's doll. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been locked in her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but she remembered the servants' and residents' indignation. She had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what do you feel like doing?", he asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed Ivory a piece of paper. But when he glanced at it...
Painting canvas 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several nuances of blue paint.
Six brushes of different sizes.
Easel
"Do you want me to find those things for you?", Ivory said, turning to the silent princess who was typing frantically, shaking her curls back and forth. "Yes?" She chuckled slightly at seeing the usually reserved princess get passionate about something. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and wasn't in her room.
"Alright. See you later?", proposed Ivory as she stood up and made her way between the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari acquiesced and sank back into her memories by wrapping herself in her thick quilt again.
She left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't within her control, such as paint.
She turned back down the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the maids.
"I've heard it said that she was possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into this room."
"I've heard that she eats children in this room."
"Does she look like a man?"
She covered her ears, for trying to ignore them wasn't working. She headed towards the royal painter's room, which was located at the east wing, second door to the left.
Ivory approached the door, which had also been worked as much as Kari's. It bore a white dragon, one of the six prime dragons, which, according to legend, had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to expose it on his door. He liked the story.
She opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, scattered crayons and papers in the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Astonishingly, she saw none of that. The room was clean and there was a red velvet backdrop with a stool right in front. On the stool, Prince Aquilo was sitting, getting his portrait drawn.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! Are you here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?", Aquilo asked Ivory, giving her a wink.
"Pardon, little prince", she replied, ignoring him partially, to look for the objects that her silent friend wanted. "I'm just here to pick up supplies."
"Ah, is the little girl going to leave very quickly?", Aquilo asked, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on her list and placed them in a box she had found. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought of it, however. "Oh my dear, you know very well that it's just a phase! It will pass when you've grown up!", he muttered.
I have to go, he said suddenly awkward, because of the prince's words, which reminded him of all the harm people said about his gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"Are you leaving us already?" The prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the royal painter's complaints.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" he rebuked.
"No one will know about it. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he wants to stay alive." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned towards Ivory. "How about a romantic appointment?" She shuddered. Of course, she had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, let alone the heir to the throne.
"Don't you know then what the word 'no' means?", he launched, brushing the prince aside.
"Oh no," Aquilo replied with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want a date with me over anyone else? Must you have a hundred or so pretenders?"
He interrupted her, still with a smile: "500, to be exact". He threw his hair back, having it fly through the cold air.
So, why me rather than someone else? I am the palace's threat. She wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." He placed his finger under his chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
